<h2>HVAC Systems in Washington</h2>
<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Washington's marine climate, characterized by mild, wet winters and warm, dry summers, creates unique HVAC requirements that differ significantly from other regions. Western Washington rarely experiences extreme temperatures, with winter lows typically staying above 25¬∞F and summer highs rarely exceeding 90¬∞F for extended periods. This moderate climate makes heat pump systems particularly attractive, as they can operate efficiently year-round without the performance degradation seen in colder climates.</p>

<p>The region's high humidity during winter months and low humidity during summer creates specific comfort challenges that modern HVAC systems must address. Air-source heat pumps have become increasingly popular due to their ability to provide both heating and cooling while operating at COP (Coefficient of Performance) ratings of 2.5-4.0 even in Washington's cooler temperatures. Ductless mini-split systems offer particular advantages in Washington's many older homes that lack existing ductwork, providing zone-controlled comfort while avoiding the energy losses associated with ducted systems.</p>

<p>Indoor air quality considerations are paramount in Washington due to extended periods of closed-window living during the rainy season, wildfire smoke events during late summer, and the prevalence of allergens from the region's abundant vegetation. High-efficiency filtration systems, heat recovery ventilators (HRVs), and humidity control become essential components of comprehensive HVAC solutions tailored to Washington's specific climate challenges.</p>

